findings_2: Anatomic Findings:  Incidental note is made of a benign-appearing 8.9 mm right  sided choroidal fissure cyst [series 3 image 14 and series 2 image 102]. Otherwise, no significant abnormality is seen elsewhere in the brain or the extracranial structures imaged.     IMPRESSION: No significant abnormality.

Study performed for research purposes. Limited MRI of the brain shows  no gross evidence of acute intracranial hemorrhage, acute infarct, significant  midline shift or mass effect. 2 likely chronic embolic infarcts involving the  right cerebellar hemisphere as seen on series 3 images 7 and 8, which are new  from the prior exam. Ventricle sizes are largely stable.

FINDINGS: There is a small extra-axial mass arising over the left posterior  frontal convexity measuring approximately 1.8 cm in diameter (series 3 image  35). This may simply represent hyperostosis or osteoma arising from the inner  table of the left frontal calvarium. However, the possibility of a small likely  calcified meningioma cannot be excluded. No mass effect on the adjacent left  frontal lobe, and no brain edema. Brain is otherwise normal in appearance for patient age. Ventricles and sulci are age-appropriate. Normal supratentorial white matter. No intra-axial mass is identified.    Normal flow voids in the major intracranial vessels. Paranasal sinuses and  mastoid air cells are grossly negative.   IMPRESSION:  Small extra-axial mass arising over the left posterior frontal convexity which may represent hyperostosis, small osteoma, or small calcified  meningioma.

Limited diagnostic images reveal T2 hyperintensity in the left  thalamus most consistent with a chronic infarct. No prior studies available for  comparison.     In the absence of a clinical history of prior stroke, consider dedicated  diagnostic MR imaging.

Ill-defined lesion demonstrating diminished signal on both the  limited T1 and axial T2-weighted images present within the lateral aspect of the  right frontal lobe (series 3, image 25). This measures approximately 17 x 7 mm.  This shows considerable susceptibility artifact and is likely partially  calcified. No mass effect or edema. No midline shift.
